John Edward: Languages skills essential for world citizens
The independent schools in Scotland have an excellent state of service in the field of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with a series of excellent exam results, as well as individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other initiatives of the whole community.
With more than 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their pupils for continuing and higher education, the career they choose and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a custom-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desired subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: ‘If you talk to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
When you talk to him in his own language, you reach his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we can't rely on English alone when we want to build relationships and a bond of trust with people from other countries.
From the recent exam results of this year, we can conclude that languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students studying foreign languages scored a high score.
The data collected from 74 schools associated with SCIS shows that 72 percent of the students scored high ('A') in Mandarin, while 72 percent of the students received German, 69 percent of French students and 63 percent of Spanish students also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now valued as much as STEM topics (science, technology, technology and mathematics) in independent school programmes and elsewhere.
A 2014 study by the British Employment and Skills Commission showed that some of the obstacles to filling vacancies were attributed 17% to a lack of linguistic knowledge, according to employers.
Language skills thus become increasingly important to prepare young people for their future career.
Now that more and more job vacancies require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Whatever career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he has a real advantage in the future with such a skill for life.
Communication directly with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person an advantage to competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation. French was the only language above 10%, with a total of 15%.
This is why investing in language education is now important for today's children.
Multiple languages, especially those of emerging economies, will give children a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland, schools choose for themselves which languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important to the United Kingdom when they look ahead to 2020, such as the Mandarin or Japan.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers specialised in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed, regardless of the future.
At present, it cannot be denied that languages in a global business environment remain vital for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be regarded as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
