National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
New research carried out on a estate in the Scottish highlands is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The hope is that the findings will give new light to the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and will contribute to future conservation activities.
The study conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland follows the common and the small dwarf bat, the brown large-eared bat and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Western Ross.
Special recording equipment shall be placed at key locations around the estate to monitor the activities of bats throughout the season.
Staff members of the NTS and volunteers will also carry out mobile investigations with the help of manual detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the screams of the bat and what kind of thing does.
A map of the habitat and a report is then produced to make a detailed picture on the landscape scale of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, NTS nature conservation consultant, hopes that the results show which habitat areas are the most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the making of pastures and how we can best maintain the forests for bats and similar species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have decreased considerably in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities affecting dormitory and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightnings can also pose a risk, such as fly catchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are actually not blind.
Their night - hunting habits, however, make their ears more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use an advanced echo-location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight route.
At the NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, bats are taken very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts, who regularly carry out investigations, inspections of dormitory and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even set up the first and only reserve for bats in Scotland at Three in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of the ten species of bats of Scotland live.
Landscape manager David Thompson says that the estate is the ideal territory for bats.
"Here in Three, we have a great environment for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But there is so much about bats not yet known, and that's why the work we're doing here and at other locations will help us to better understand what they need in order to thrive."
It stresses the importance of controlling bats before maintenance work is carried out, as the possible unconscious destruction of a dormitory can lead to the death of 400 female bats and their boy, possibly eliminating a full local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill them, to harass them or to disturb them or to destroy their dorms.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust, asked the public to make a contribution to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and many of our species, we simply don't know how their populations are."
